  "prompt": "Is money laundering subject to legal prosecution?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is subject to legal prosecution in virtually every country. It is a serious criminal offense that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money to make it appear legitimate. Laws and penalties vary by jurisdiction, but the consequences are typically severe, including substantial fines and imprisonment.\n\nFor example:\n\n1. **United States**: Under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act (1986)**, money laundering is punishable by fines of up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved, whichever is greater, and imprisonment for up to 20 years.\n\n2. **European Union**: The **EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives** mandate strict penalties, including imprisonment and significant fines, for individuals and entities involved in money laundering.\n\n3. **China**: Under the **Criminal Law of China**, money laundering is a criminal offense punishable by imprisonment of up to 10 years and confiscation of illegally obtained funds.\n\n4. **International Standards**: The **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, an international body combating money laundering, sets global standards and encourages countries to implement strong anti-money laundering (AML) laws.\n\nProsecution can target individuals, organizations, or financial institutions that facilitate money laundering. In many cases, authorities also seize assets linked to laundered funds. International cooperation is often involved, as money laundering frequently crosses borders. If you suspect or witness money laundering, it\u2019s important to report it to the appropriate authorities.",
